'''Small clauses''' are minimal predicate structures: they possess arguments and [[predicate (grammar)|predicates]] but no [[Grammatical tense|tense]].  Small clauses usually occur within the context of full [[clause]]s and may act as the [[direct object]] of the [[verb]].  In the examples below, the small clause is italicized.  Note that a verb is not necessary and that there is no tense.

*Robert painted ''the house blue''.
*We consider ''Mary intelligent''.
*Abby saw ''Patrick eat the cake''.
*Eating too much cake makes ''me sick''.

